5.3. The Prerogatives of the Executive Power -- t5 .4. The Myth of Responsibility -- t5.5. The Internal Division of the Executive Power -- tChapter 6. The Rule-of-Law State and lts Executors -- t6.1. Rule by Law and the Rule-of-Law State -- t6.2. The Administration of Justice -- tChapter 7. Constitutional Adjudication -- t7 .1. Who Guards the Guardians? -- tChapter 8. Fundamental Rights -- t8.1. Freedom and Human Rights -- t8.2. Defining Fundamental Rights -- t8.3. What Do Fundamental Rights Imply? -- t8.4. When Fundamental Rights May Be Restricted: Reconciling the State with Freedom in Constitutionalism -- t8.5. What Purpose Do Fundamental Rights Serve If Abused? -- t8.6. How Precise Should the Definition Be?0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUntil the previous decade, constitutionalism in Eastern Europe was considered to be an outmoded concept of the nineteenth century. Changes in the region, however, have brought back the fundamental question of the need to restrict government power through social self-binding. This book discusses the mechanisms of such restriction, including different forms of the separation of powers and constitutional review. It relates the theoretical and practical importance of the issue to the present world-wide discontent with majoritarian democracy and the growing disrepute of parliaments. Increasing executive efficiency is, however, a threat to fundamental rights, and the battlecry of efficiency is often only a means to new despotism and inefficiency. A careful re-evaluation of the concept of constitutionalism assists in the search for a useful balance between majoritarianism and rights, and in the avoidance of all forms of public tyranny. Written in non-technical language and using the most important English, American, French, and German examples of constitutional history, the book also examines East European (in particular, Russian) and Latin American examples, in part to illustrate certain dead-ends in constitutional development. It is intended to be an introduction for all those concerned with liberty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aEastern Europe.  aHungary.  aRule of law.  aconstitutionalism.  ademocracy.1 aHolmes, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSajó, András, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863879423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863879/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK